── PRIOR REVIEW HISTORY for UI/UX (initial review + prior review-fixes passes — do NOT re-report resolved findings) ──

### initial review — Reviewed the entire changeset (src/app.css, src/app.ts, src/app/dom-builders.ts, render-browse.ts, render-orchestrator.ts, toolbar-handlers.ts). The work is overwhelmingly UI-facing: a new search-wrapper with overlaid icon + CSS-driven clear button, debounced instant search, a loading spinner, Bootstrap Icons on every menu item, a right-click current-directory context menu, and whole-row click-to-browse. Visual styling and interaction polish are generally solid (correct box-sizing fix on menu anchors, pointer cursors on navigable rows, clamped menu positioning, focus-within reflection on the upload label). The main gaps are accessibility: the search input has no real accessible name (placeholder only), decorative icons are not hidden from AT, the spinner is not announced, the row-menu advertises menu semantics it does not implement, and a couple of small contrast/touch-target/copy issues.
- [high] Search input is labeled only by its placeholder, with no accessible name — src/app.ts:75-77
    The toolbar search input is created with `type='text'` and `placeholder='Search...'` but no `aria-label` and no associated `<label>`. A placeholder is not an accessible name: it vanishes the moment the user types, has low contrast, and is an unreliable/last-resort source in the accessible-name computation. Notably the upload input right next to it correctly gets `uploadInput.setAttribute('aria-label', 'Upload files')`, so this is an inconsistency. Screen-reader users get either no name or a fragile one. WCAG 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) and 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) require a programmatically determinable name. Add an `aria-label` (the wrapper holds no visible text label, so `aria-label` is the right mechanism, matching the upload input).
- [medium] Decorative Bootstrap-Icons <i> glyphs are not hidden from assistive tech — src/app/dom-builders.ts:585-591 (makeIcon)
    Every icon added in this changeset — the in-input search glyph, the clear button's `bi-x-lg`, the close button's `bi-x-lg`, the spinner's `bi-arrow-repeat`, and all the menu-item glyphs produced by `makeIcon` ('upload', 'download', 'trash', 'arrows-move', 'files', 'folder-plus') — are `<i>` elements with no `aria-hidden`. Bootstrap Icons render their glyph via a CSS `::before { content: '\f...' }` rule, and some screen readers announce generated content / private-use-area code points as stray noise. Because each icon is paired with a visible text label (or, for the clear/close buttons, an `aria-label`), the icon is purely decorative and must be hidden from AT per WCAG 1.3.1. The central fix is in `makeIcon` (covers all menu-item icons); the few icons created inline in app.ts and render-orchestrator.ts must be patched separately.
- [medium] Search loading spinner is visual-only; screen readers get no 'loading' announcement — src/app/render-orchestrator.ts:79-86
    When a search is in flight, sighted users see a centered spinning `bi-arrow-repeat`, but the spinner container is a plain `<div>` with no `role='status'` and no `aria-live` region, so assistive-tech users receive no feedback that work is happening (and the previous results simply vanish with no explanation). WCAG 4.1.3 (Status Messages) calls for status messages to be announced programmatically. Mark the spinner wrapper as a polite live region so its presence is announced when it appears.
- [medium] Row menu advertises `aria-haspopup='true'` (menu) but does not implement the menu pattern — src/app/dom-builders.ts:301-310 (makeRowMenu)
    The per-row ⋮ button sets `aria-haspopup='true'` (which per spec is equivalent to `aria-haspopup='menu'`) and toggles `aria-expanded`, signaling to AT users that activating it opens a menu widget with arrow-key item navigation, Home/End, and focus moving to the first item on open. The actual dropdown is a plain `<div class='row-menu'>` containing `<button class='btn'>` / `<a class='btn'>` items with no `role='menu'`/`role='menuitem'`, no focus move into the menu on open, and no arrow-key handling — only Tab/Shift+Tab and Escape work. This expectation mismatch is confusing for screen-reader users. Either complete the menu semantics or downgrade to a plain disclosure. The lower-risk, self-contained fix is to complete the semantics by adding the roles.
- [medium] Move/Copy prompts use developer jargon ('relative destination path') — src/app/dom-builders.ts:340-360 (makeRowMenu Move/Copy handlers)
    The Move and Copy actions use `window.prompt('Move to relative destination path:', entry.path)` and `window.prompt('Copy to relative destination path:', entry.path)`. 'Relative destination path' is internal/developer terminology that end users of a file browser will not understand; it also does not tell them the path is relative to the storage root or how separators work. The copy should be plain and action-oriented, consistent with the rest of the UI (e.g. 'New directory name:', 'Delete "x"?'). The prompts pre-fill `entry.path` as the default, which is a helpful hint and should stay.
- [low] Placeholder text and search icon sit just below the 4.5:1 AA contrast threshold — src/app.css:189-198
    The search input placeholder and the overlaid icons use `#9a9a9a` on the input background `#333337`. That combination measures ~4.47:1 contrast — fractionally under the 4.5:1 WCAG AA threshold for normal-size text (the placeholder is 13px, not large text). The same `#9a9a9a` on the body background `#1e1e1e` is fine (~5.9:1). Because the placeholder is the only label hint sighted users get before typing (and doubles as the search affordance), nudging it above threshold is worthwhile. Icon glyphs are held to the 3:1 non-text contrast threshold, which this passes, but raising the color also helps the clear/search icon legibility.
- [low] Clear button has a hover state but no focus style and is below the 24px touch-target minimum — src/app.css:224-240
    The `.clear-btn` defines `.clear-btn:hover { color: #e6e6e6; }` but no `:focus`/`:focus-visible` rule, so unlike the toolbar input (which gains a blue focus border) and the upload label (which has an explicit `:focus-within` outline), keyboard focus on the clear button relies on the browser default outline only — inconsistent with the rest of the toolbar. The button is also only ~20px tall/wide (`bi-x-lg` ~16px glyph + `padding: 2px`), below the 24×24 CSS px minimum in WCAG 2.5.8 (Target Size, Minimum) and well under the 44px enhanced target. Add a visible focus ring matching the app accent and enlarge the hit area.
- [low] Loading spinner shows for search but not for folder navigation, creating inconsistent feedback — src/app/render-orchestrator.ts:74-86
    The new spinner is gated behind `if (route.view === 'search')`, so navigating into a folder (a `browse` route) clears the results and fetches with no loading affordance, while searching shows a spinner for the same kind of async fetch. On slow connections this looks like a hang or a frozen listing for browse navigation. The `render()` already clears `resultsEl.innerHTML` synchronously for both routes, so the browse path shows a blank panel until the fetch resolves. For consistent perceived performance, show the same spinner (or a neutral one) for browse routes too.

